# Agent Gradle cache

Cursor sandboxes may set `GRADLE_USER_HOME` to an ephemeral `cursor-sandbox-cache` path, forcing a **cold Gradle wrapper download** and empty dependency cache every run.

## Always do this for Gradle in agent shells

Before `./gradlew` (or use the repo hook script which already fixes this):

```bash
source launcher/scripts/ensure-host-gradle-home.sh
./gradlew …
```

Or inline:

```bash
GRADLE_USER_HOME="$HOME/.gradle" ./gradlew …
```

## One-time local setup (recommended)

```bash
chmod +x tools/dev/setup-cursor-sandbox.sh
./tools/dev/setup-cursor-sandbox.sh
```

Then restart Cursor or open a new agent chat. This writes `~/.cursor/sandbox.json` with `enableSharedBuildCache` and read/write access to `~/.gradle`.

Repo-level [`.cursor/sandbox.json`](../sandbox.json) enables shared build cache for this workspace; the setup script adds the user-specific Gradle path.

## Optional Cursor settings

- **Agents → Legacy Terminal Tool** — fewer sandbox env injections.
- **Command allowlist** — add `./gradlew` so Gradle runs outside the sandbox when approved.

## What reusing ~/.gradle speeds up

| Cache | Location under ~/.gradle |
|-------|-------------------------|
| Wrapper distribution (no re-download of gradle-8.x-bin.zip) | `wrapper/dists/` |
| Dependencies | `caches/` |
| Configuration cache | `configuration-cache/` |

Pre-commit [`ktlint-check.sh`](../../launcher/scripts/ktlint-check.sh) sources `ensure-host-gradle-home.sh` automatically.
